            <fr:title text="Preferatory notes about Galois Theory">Preferatory notes about Galois Theory</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Galois theory combines everything we've studied so far in abstract algebra: we have fields which are super nice rings (relying on everything discussed in the <fr:link href="/iaa-0008/" title="Traditional Introduction to Rings" uri="http://localhost:8000/iaa-0008/" display-uri="iaa-0008" type="local">Traditional Introduction to Rings</fr:link>) and we may view some fields as vector spaces over another (relying on everything discussed in the <fr:link href="/iaa-0009/" title="Traditional Introduction to Modules" uri="http://localhost:8000/iaa-0009/" display-uri="iaa-0009" type="local">Traditional Introduction to Modules</fr:link>).</html:p>
            <html:p>We can translate "roots of a polynomial" into "field extensions", and then study the symmetries of field extensions leaving the base field invariant. This relies on everything we learned in the <fr:link href="/iaa-0001/" title="Traditional Introduction to Groups" uri="http://localhost:8000/iaa-0001/" display-uri="iaa-0001" type="local">Traditional Introduction to Groups</fr:link>.</html:p>
            <html:p>In other words, Galois theory combines everything we have learned into a single application (i.e., solving polynomials over fields). <fr:link href="/emmy-noether/" title="Emmy Noether" uri="http://localhost:8000/emmy-noether/" display-uri="emmy-noether" type="local">Emmy Noether</fr:link> is responsible for this presentation of material, but <fr:link href="/bartel-van-der-waerden/" title="Bartel L. van der Waerden" uri="http://localhost:8000/bartel-van-der-waerden/" display-uri="bartel-van-der-waerden" type="local">Bartel L. van der Waerden</fr:link> usually gets credit for it since it's basically the content of <fr:link href="/van-der-waerden-1949-modern1/" title="Modern Algebra, Vol. I" uri="http://localhost:8000/van-der-waerden-1949-modern1/" display-uri="van-der-waerden-1949-modern1" type="local">Modern Algebra, Vol. I</fr:link>...but people don't realize that Emmy Noether is the person who wrote the outline and highlighted the importance of this structure to the presentation of material.</html:p>
            <html:p>Before I forget, these are mostly based on my notes and the notes of Zavosh Amir-Khosravi (who used them for Caltech's Math 5C course for Spring quarter 2018).</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
